I agree with mark these plots look fine. It is to be expected that the distributions are not perfect
gaussians especially when radiative effects are included which lead to asymmetric distributions (e.g. in the
missing energy distributions, or the pm component along q as seen in h(e,e’p)). Here are a few more comments
regarding the various questions.

Question 4: the choice of PWIA calculations (excluding exotic effects) should only affect the ratio if different
off-shell e-p cross sections are involved which are expected to be small to these high momentum transfers, so I would
expect that peak position and peak width will be unaffected but the overall scale can be different depending on the
momentum distribution used. (If you want to get carried away you could calculate the ratio of Misak’s PWIA to Laget’s
PWIA as an illustration).

Question 6: As I remember we do not have any new data for 70 degree at pm = 500 MeV/c except the old Hall A experiment
at 3.5 GeV/c and an additional data point there would be useful. I do not consider this as a normalization point as
these are those at much lower missing momentum values. If time is critical I would even consider dropping this point.
At high missing momenta (pm > 0.8 GeV/c) calculation differ by much more than a few % and a 5 - 10% normalization
uncertainty is irrelevant especially if the statistical precision is of the same oder or larger

Question 6: Show an angular distribution calculated with Laget compared to Misak with AV18 and CD-Bonn, this
should answer this questions

Question 8: You could take a typical angular distribution and convolute it with the distribution that you got
from the SIMC calculations. This would demonstrate how the resolution affects the measurements (I would expect very little).

Question 9: This experiment was designed to explore the hi-pm part of the d(e,e’p)n cross section in a kinematic area
where we expect FSI to be small. There is not enough kinematic coverage to also extract an angular distribution at large pm,
hence this proposal.
